<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="95" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="95">Diagnosis.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="95">
Female can be recognized by its black large body size (20-26 mm); mesosoma and T1 covered with fulvous hairs (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 16" captionStartId="F16" captionText="Figure 16. Megachile (Callomegachile) monticola Smith, 1853, female a lateral view b protruding tubercle at base of clypeus (arrow) c frontal view of mandible and labrum d dorsal view of metasoma e spine at apical tibia f lateral view of metasoma and scopa." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.997.34935.figure16" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/479645" pageId="0" pageNumber="95">16a</figureCitation>
); base of clypeus with large protruding tubercle (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 16" captionStartId="F16" captionText="Figure 16. Megachile (Callomegachile) monticola Smith, 1853, female a lateral view b protruding tubercle at base of clypeus (arrow) c frontal view of mandible and labrum d dorsal view of metasoma e spine at apical tibia f lateral view of metasoma and scopa." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.997.34935.figure16" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/479645" pageId="0" pageNumber="95">16b</figureCitation>
); mandibles elongate with three teeth and small tubercle at base; labrum oblong with lateral impression (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 16" captionStartId="F16" captionText="Figure 16. Megachile (Callomegachile) monticola Smith, 1853, female a lateral view b protruding tubercle at base of clypeus (arrow) c frontal view of mandible and labrum d dorsal view of metasoma e spine at apical tibia f lateral view of metasoma and scopa." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.997.34935.figure16" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/479645" pageId="0" pageNumber="95">16c</figureCitation>
); black scopa.
</paragraph>
